{"author":"Iso Tester","data":{"body":"## Completion verification — FAIL\n\nReviewed against all Acceptance Criteria and the Success Criterion. Every criterion is grounded in tool output from the repository.\n\n---\n\n### Evidence base\n\nKey files confirmed present and read:\n\n| File | Status |\n|------|--------|\n| `src/rebar/reducer/_managed_refs.py` | ✅ exists, fully implemented |\n| `src/rebar/reducer/_processors.py` | ✅ folds managed_refs in process_create, process_link, process_edit(parent_id), seeds in process_snapshot |\n| `src/rebar/reducer/_state.py` | ✅ `managed_refs: []` in `make_initial_state()` |\n| `docs/managed-refs.md` | ✅ exists, documents gate contract, field, and future reclamation hook |\n| `tests/scripts/reducer/test_managed_refs.py` | ✅ 9 tests covering fold, idempotency, seeding, compaction roundtrip, gate |\n| `tests/unit/rebar_reconciler/diffing/test_link_removal_sync.py` | ✅ gate consumed in differ, same-pass suppression tested |\n| `tests/unit/rebar_reconciler/diffing/test_parent_detach_sync.py` | ✅ parent detach gates on managed_refs |\n| `src/rebar/_engine/rebar_reconciler/outbound_differ.py:518,1126` | ✅ `should_propagate_removal` imported and called for both parent and link paths |\n\n---\n\n### Per-criterion verdicts\n\n**AC1 — Reducer maintains `compiled_state.managed_refs` as strictly-monotonic, deterministically-sorted union…** ✅ MET\n\n`_managed_refs.py` exports `add_managed_ref` (idempotent, monotonic, never removes). `process_create` calls it for the initial `parent_id` (`_processors.py:60`); `process_link` calls it for `(relation, resolved_target)` (`_processors.py:248`); `process_edit` calls it when `field_name == \"parent_id\"` (`_processors.py:351-352`). `process_unlink` only filters `state[\"deps\"]` — never touches `managed_refs` (`_processors.py:251-254`). Serialized as `sorted(refs)` by `serialize_managed_refs`. `make_initial_state()` seeds the field as `[]` so the `process_edit` guard (`if field_name not in state: continue`) never silently drops it.\n\n**AC2 — Reducer seeds `managed_refs` from current deps + parent_id when absent; test proves pre-feature compacted ticket's unlink propagates** ✅ MET (seeding confirmed; propagation chain covered by separate unit tests)\n\n`process_snapshot` at `_processors.py:542-543` seeds from `seed_managed_refs_from_current(state)` when `\"managed_refs\" not in compiled_state`. `test_snapshot_without_managed_refs_is_seeded_from_current` (test file line 92-112) writes a SNAPSHOT with no `managed_refs` key (simulating a pre-feature compacted ticket), reduces it, and asserts the legacy parent and dep refs appear in `managed_refs`. The propagation half is covered by the gate unit tests (`test_gate_propagates_only_managed_refs`) — a seeded ref in `managed_refs` causes `should_propagate_removal` to return True, which the differ acts on.\n\n**AC3 — `managed_refs` survives `compact_ticket` (restored by `process_snapshot`): removal before OR after compaction still propagates; covered by a compact-then-reconcile test** ❌ NOT MET\n\n`test_managed_refs_survive_compaction_roundtrip` (test file lines 129-148) verifies that refs survive the SNAPSHOT roundtrip at the **reducer** level: it writes events, reduces, writes the compiled_state as a SNAPSHOT, reduces again, and asserts the refs are unchanged. This covers the \"compaction survival\" half. However, the AC explicitly calls for \"a compact-then-reconcile test\" — i.e., a test that compacts, then writes a post-compaction UNLINK (or exercises the outbound differ with the compacted ticket), and verifies the removal propagates through the reconciler. No such end-to-end compact→unlink→reconcile test exists anywhere in the test tree. The two halves are tested in isolation (reducer-only compaction roundtrip + separate differ-only gate tests), never combined into the single \"compact-then-reconcile\" test the AC specifies.\n\n**AC4 — SNAPSHOT byte-parity preserved (existing byte-parity guard passes)** ✅ MET\n\n`tests/interfaces/store/test_canonical_event_bytes.py` exercises the full lifecycle including `compact-on-close` which writes a real SNAPSHOT from `compiled_state`. `managed_refs` is included in `make_initial_state()` and serialized via `serialize_managed_refs` (deterministic sorted list), so every SNAPSHOT that carries `managed_refs` is byte-stable.\n\n**AC5 — `should_propagate_removal` gate exists, provider-agnostic, defaults missing managed_refs to empty, unit-tested for REMOVE-vs-ADOPT** ✅ MET\n\n`_managed_refs.py:139-152` implements `should_propagate_removal(kind, target, local_ticket) -> bool`. No Jira-specific logic (operates on local (kind, target) pairs). `test_gate_propagates_only_managed_refs` and `test_gate_defaults_missing_managed_refs_to_no_removal` cover REMOVE vs ADOPT decisions and empty/missing defaults. Both parent and link paths import and call it (`outbound_differ.py:518,1126`).\n\n**AC6 — Operator-facing regression: unlink a managed ref locally, run two reconcile passes, the ref stays removed (not resurrected)** ❌ NOT MET\n\n`test_outbound_remove_suppresses_inbound_link_readd` (`test_link_removal_sync.py:147-169`) covers the **single-pass, same-pass coordination** scenario: outbound emits REMOVE, inbound with that context suppresses the re-add. This demonstrates the churn is fixed within one pass.\n\nThe AC requires a **two-pass** regression test: pass 1 sends the DELETE to Jira; pass 2 runs with an updated Jira snapshot (the link is now absent) and must emit zero mutations — the ref does **not** resurrect. No such test exists. The closest tests are `test_managed_link_absent_locally_emits_remove` (pass-1 outbound remove), `test_outbound_remove_suppresses_inbound_link_readd` (same-pass inbound suppression), and `test_link_still_present_locally_emits_no_remove` (no-remove when local dep still present), but none simulates pass-2 state (Jira snapshot with link absent after deletion) and verifies zero mutations.\n\n**AC7 — `docs/` documents the pattern (gate contract, `managed_refs` field, future reconcile-time reclamation hook)** ✅ MET\n\n`docs/managed-refs.md` documents: the `managed_refs` field and its semantics (lines 38-87); the `should_propagate_removal` gate contract with its signature and True/False semantics (lines 91-104); the future reclamation hook as an explicit out-of-scope item (lines 113-121); the extension template for new providers (lines 123-127).\n\n**Success Criterion — Reusable, provider-agnostic primitive both parent and link removal sync consume, with no Jira-specific logic in the shared gate** ✅ MET\n\n`should_propagate_removal` operates on local `(kind, target)` pairs; all Jira-specific resolution (key → local_id) happens in the caller before the gate is invoked. Both `_is_parent_managed_removal` (`outbound_differ.py:510-526`) and `_diff_links_removal` (`outbound_differ.py:1120-1175`) consume it.\n\n---\n\n### Summary\n\nSix of seven acceptance criteria and the success criterion are met. Two criteria fail:\n\n1. **AC3** — The AC calls for a \"compact-then-reconcile test.\" The `test_managed_refs_survive_compaction_roundtrip` test demonstrates compaction survival at the reducer level only; no test chains compaction → post-compaction event → reconciler/differ path to verify removal propagates end-to-end across the compaction boundary.\n\n2. **AC6** — The AC requires a two-pass operator regression. The existing test covers same-pass suppression. A second-pass stability test — where the Jira snapshot reflects the deletion from pass 1 and pass 2 produces zero mutations — does not exist.\n\n**Verdict: FAIL**"},"env_id":"ade0f2ef-51cc-45a2-bb97-c09846cd3df5","event_type":"COMMENT","timestamp":1782542168332686001,"uuid":"6382c3f6-8c84-494c-9408-79b111231ab4"}